description: From Middle English thringen, from Old English þringan (“to press, squeeze, crowd”), from Proto-West Germanic *þringwan, from Proto-Germanic *þrinhwaną (“to press, throng, crush”), from Proto-Indo-European *trenkʷ- (“to beat, hew, press”).

verbs.description: thring (third-person singular simple present thrings, present participle thringing, simple past thrang or thrung or thringed, past participle thrung or thringed)

entries.meaning: (transitive, Northern England, Scotland) To thrust; crowd; press; squeeze.
(intransitive, Northern England, Scotland) To push; to force one's way.
